Now I can see exactly what's happening. Let me read the relevant section of server.js to understand the static file serving logic:

```
const legacyPublicPath = path.join(__dirname, 'public');
console.log('[server] Serving React SPA from client/dist');
app.use(express.static(reactBuildPath));
console.log('[server] React build not found, serving legacy public/');
app.use(express.static(legacyPublicPath));
```

So the server checks if `client/dist` exists:
- If it does → serves the React SPA from `client/dist`


- If not → falls back to `public/` (legacy)

The previous agents were editing files in `public/`, but since `client/dist` exists, those legacy files are never actually served—the React SPA takes over completely. That's why their changes had no effect. I need to look at the React app structure to find where the job board and job creation pages are actually implemented.

